review_text: Very good course. I learnt a lot about LLM Engineering and was able to use this knowledge in my regular job.
Solid 8 weeks! It has been an awesome journey to start from knowing nothing about LLMs to actually mastering a lot of stuff.

What a masterpiece of a practical LLM Engineering, no gaps at all. Everything is covered all the way to deployment for AI. A lot of great background information besides all the code needed to run all the examples.
This is a life changing course so far. Meticulously described each chapter with hands-on. Looking forward to your Agentic AI course...

Well... I took this course to learn about LLMS... and I learnt plenty about these models and their applications for different use cases. Thanks to Ed Donner for his excellent effort. I enjoyed taking this course and am happy that my objective is fulfilled... I will keep referring to this course as and when necessary... :-)
Exemplary course build-up over the time. Thanks for preparing this fantastic code.

Excellent course! Ed explained each concept clearly and at a great pace. The projects were practical and diverse. The RAG-based knowledge worker and fine-tuning a LLaMA model using QLoRA for price prediction was impressive. A perfect blend of theory and hands-on AI engineering. Highly recommended!
Einer der besten Kurse, die ich bisher gemacht habe. Ed Donner ist ein hervorragender Trainer, der den Stoff gut vermittelt, dabei sehr motivierend ist und auch Spaß vermittelt. Absolut Spitze!

I'm already a Senior Data Scientist and have done three more courses on LLMs (Coursera, DeepLearning.ai, and Udemy). I have to say this was by far the most well-organized and helpful. I can also appreciate how you've been trying to accomodate for a variety of skill levels of your audience: describing further when required some concepts.
Amazing course ! I was glued to it for the entire duration. It definitely elevated my knowledge in LLMs to another level. Highly recommended!

The RAG stuff in week 5 is very easy to see tons of real world uses for. The use of Jupyter Notebooks and Google Collab throughout helps make the coding easier to follow along with, and the code has been updated regularly by the instructor up to the time I'm writing this in July 2025.

On the positive -

A "Level 300" continuation of this course might be a less code intensive dive into mastering AI model customizations on top of more macro frameworks (like interacting with a human manager via Slack with a CrewAI team of reasoning frontier model coding agents using MCPs committing to git branches, review each other's code, unit tests even shown out there) for tuning different coding models per the documentation of a particular API (imagine agentic coding of Blender bpy scripts to custom-build a described animation or building a simple game in Unity/C#) after having the AI tuned on the specific API documentation to become a product specialist. For bonus points, have it leverage community forums and postings to augment its subtask efforts as needed or open issues in git[hub|lab] for humans or other agents. The latest frontier models could even use multimodal verification of the visual results feedback to the coder agents as shown in some white papers. It sounds mind-blowing but you have to agree the current pace of development will make this old hat a few years from now. Just dreaming...
